'''Umenoki Site''' (梅木遺跡, Umenoki Iseki) is an [[archaeological site]] in [[Nishi-Ōmuro-chō]], [[Maebashi City]], [[Gunma Prefecture]], Japan, featuring remains of a [[Kofun period]] [[chieftain]]’s residence.

== Overview ==
The site is located at the southern base of [[Mount Akagi]], within the grounds of [[Ōmuro Park]]. It is believed the residence was rectangular and enclosed by moats and fences. However, major features were eroded by repeated flooding of the nearby Katsura River, leaving only fragments. Excavations have revealed pillar holes and an expanded moat structure at the southwestern corner, suggesting the presence of a gate.

The moat is estimated to have measured about 85 meters on its outer edge, 65 meters on its inner edge, and encompassed an area of approximately 6,500 square meters. The moat was constructed over a mid-Kofun period [[pit dwelling]]. Volcanic ash (Hr-FA [[tephra]]) from the early 6th-century eruption of [[Mount Haruna]] found at the bottom of the moat indicates the residence was built in the late 5th century and used until the early 6th century.{{Sfn|Maebashi City Board of Education, Cultural Heritage Division|2016|p=19}}

Approximately 400 meters southwest of this site lies the [[:en:Maefutago_Kofun|Mae-Futago Kofun]], a keyhole-shaped tomb from the early 6th century, which suggests a potential connection to the Umenoki Site.

